ah]]\n|religion      = [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|Mormonism]]\n|website       = {{url|salmon.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Matthew James \"Matt\" Salmon''' (born January 21, 1958) is the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] representative for {{ushr|Arizona|5}}.  The district is based in [[Mesa, Arizona|Mesa]] and includes most of the [[East Valley (Phoenix metropolitan area)|East Valley]].  He previously represented the district, then numbered as the [[Arizona's 1st congressional district|1st District]], from 1995 to 2001.  In 2002, he lost to [[Janet Napolitano]] in a highly competitive [[Governor of Arizona|governor]]'s race. He regained his old congressional seat in the 2012 election. Salmon and his wife Nancy have been married for 34 years. They have four children and seven grandchildren.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matt Salmon \u2013 Family|url=http://www.salmon.house.gov/about/full-biography|publisher=Salmon.house.gov|accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn February 25, 2016, Salmon announced his retirement from politics.<ref name=PoliticoRetirement>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/02/matt-salmon-to-retire-219769|title=Rep. Salmon announces retirement|work=[[Politico]]|last=Sherman|first=Jake|date=February 25, 2016|accessdate=May 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\nSalmon was born in [[Salt Lake City, Utah]]. He is a member of [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]. He speaks fluent [[Mandarin Chinese]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/01/new-house-members-of-113th-congress-q-r-s-86146_Page2.html#MS |title=New House members of 113th Congress: Q-R-S \u2013 Politico Staff |publisher=Politico.Com |date= |accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Arizona Senate (1991\u20131995)==\n\n===Elections===\nIn 1990, he ran for the [[Arizona Senate]] in the 21st Senate District based in [[Mesa, Arizona]]. In the Republican primary, he defeated incumbent State Senator [[Jerry Gillespie (politician)|Jerry Gillespie]], who was controversial due to his support of impeached Governor [[Evan Mecham]] and his vote against the [[Martin Luther King holiday]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=124990 |title=Candidate \u2013 Jerry Gillespie |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> In the general election, he defeated Democrat Bill Hegarty 60%\u201340%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=303906 |title=AZ State Senate 21 Race \u2013 Nov 06, 1990 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> In 1992, he won re-election to a second term unopposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=272706 |title=AZ State Senate 21 Race \u2013 Nov 03, 1992 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:Matt salmon.jpg|thumb|right|Previous Salmon Congressional Photograph]]\nIn 1992, he was elected to a new leadership position called assistant majority leader.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hOxPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=u1UDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6941956764&dq=matt+salmon&hl=en]  {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> He served that position until 1995.\n\nIn 1993, he sponsored legislation that created new drug test programs for employers.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ADSB&s_site=azstarnet&f_site=azstarnet&f_sitename=Arizona+Daily+Star%2C+The+%28AZ%29&p_multi=ADSB&p_theme=gannett&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EACE58C617216A2&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | title=Workers win as two bills die in House | work=Arizona Daily Star | date=April 16, 1993}}</ref> That year, he also called for an independent study of the Department of Economic Services' child welfare agency.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ADSB&s_site=azstarnet&f_site=azstarnet&f_sitename=Arizona+Daily+Star%2C+The+%28AZ%29&p_multi=ADSB&p_theme=gannett&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EACE59BAB73C220&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | title=2 legislators call for greater scrutiny of child welfare agency's operations | work=Arizona Daily Star | date=November 19, 1993}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* Senate Appropriations Committee<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ADSB&s_site=azstarnet&f_site=azstarnet&f_sitename=Arizona+Daily+Star%2C+The+%28AZ%29&p_multi=ADSB&p_theme=gannett&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EACE59B28445D16&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | title=Lawmakers from Pima stir anger; Push for tax equity irks Maricopa legislators | work=Arizona Daily Star | date=November 14, 1993}}</ref>\n* Senate Indian Gambling Committee (Co-Chairman)<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ADSB&s_site=azstarnet&f_site=azstarnet&f_sitename=Arizona+Daily+Star%2C+The+%28AZ%29&p_multi=ADSB&p_theme=gannett&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EACE58F776AC95A&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | title=Symington calls special session on Indian gaming to begin June 7 | work=Arizona Daily Star | date=May 27, 1993}}</ref>\n* Senate Rules Committee (Chairman)<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=madPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=2lIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=70652308711&dq=matt+salmon+committee&hl=en]  {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (1995\u20132001)==\n\n===Elections===\n;1994\nIncumbent U.S. Congressman [[Sam Coppersmith]], a Democrat, decided to retire after one term in what was then the 1st District in order to run for the U.S. Senate. Salmon won the Republican primary with a plurality of 39% in a five-candidate field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=249429 |title=AZ District 1 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Sep 13, 1994 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> During his first Congressional election campaign, [[term limit]]s were a high-profile issue. Salmon was one of many candidates nationwide who pledged to serve only three terms in Congress. In the general election, he defeated Democratic State Senator [[Chuck Blanchard]] 56%\u201339%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=3724 |title=AZ District 1 Race \u2013 Nov 08, 1994 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;1996\nHe won re-election to a second term with 60% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=3210 |title=AZ District 1 Race \u2013 Nov 05, 1996 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;1998\nHe won re-election to a third term with 65% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=3209 |title=AZ District 1 Race \u2013 Nov 03, 1998 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;2000\nHe honored his campaign pledge and did not seek re-election to a fourth term in 2000.\n\n===Tenure===\nHe signed the [[Contract with America]].<ref>[http://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/congress/july-dec98/gop_11-9.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301082041/http://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/congress/july-dec98/gop_11-9.html |date=March 1, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, he unsuccessfully advocated carving [[Ronald Reagan]]'s face into [[Mount Rushmore]], claiming that the former President had won the [[Cold War]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/288213.stm | work=BBC News | title=Reagan for Rushmore | date=March 1, 1999}}</ref> Salmon was instrumental in obtaining the January 29, 2000 release of U.S. based academic researcher [[Song Yongyi]] from detention in China on spying charges.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/623235.stm |title=ASIA-PACIFIC &#124; Academic freed by China flies home |publisher=News.bbc.co.uk |date=2000-01-29 |accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref>\n\n;Accomplishments\n* \"Watchdog of the Treasury\" award six years in a row\n* \"Taxpayer Hero\" award from [[Citizens Against Government Waste]]\n* \"Friend of Small Business\" award from the [[National Federation of Independent Business]]\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* [[House International Relations Committee]]<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=BBAB&d_place=BBAB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F99F8110CA5B9E6&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | title=China reports some US congressmen apologize for bombing of embassy | work=Xinhua news | date=May 15, 1999}}</ref>\n\n==Inter-congressional years (2001\u20132011)==\n\n===2002 gubernatorial election===\n{{Main article|Arizona gubernatorial election, 2002}}\nIncumbent Republican [[Arizona Governor]] [[Jane Dee Hull]] was ineligible for re-election in 2002. In the Republican primary, Salmon defeated [[Arizona Secretary of State]] Betsy Bayless and Arizona Treasurer [[Carol Springer]] 56%\u201330%\u201314%. He won every county in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=86 |title=AZ Governor \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Sep 10, 2002 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> In the general election, he faced Democratic nominee and [[Arizona Attorney General]] [[Janet Napolitano]], Libertarian nominee [[Barry Hess]], and former Arizona Secretary of State [[Richard D. Mahoney]] (who ran as an independent, but was previously a Democrat). Napolitano defeated Salmon 46%\u201345%, a difference of just 11,819 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=29 |title=AZ Governor Race \u2013 Nov 05, 2002 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Political activism===\nAfter that race, he served as a lobbyist and chairman of the Arizona [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. In 2007, he served as campaign manager to businessman [[Scott Smith (mayor)|Scott Smith]]'s successful campaign for Mayor of [[Mesa, Arizona|Mesa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ARPB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11901B37B5BC8BC8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Ex-Builder Seeks Mesa Mayoral Seat|accessdate=December 5, 2008|date=June 1, 2006|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|author=Nelson, Gary}}</ref> In 2008, he became President of the [[Competitive Telecommunications Association]], a Washington, D.C.-based trade association.<ref>{{cite web|author=Timberlake Membership Software, 703-591-4232, www.timberlakepublishing.com |url=http://www.comptel.org/content.asp?contentid=1100 |title=Comptel |publisher=Comptel |date=December 4, 2007 |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (2013\u2013present)==\n[[File:Matt Salmon speaking in June 3, 2014 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Salmon speaking on June 3, 2014]]\n\n===Second congressional stint===\n{{main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Arizona, 2012#District 5}}\nIn April 2011, Salmon announced he would seek his old congressional seat, which was now numbered as [[Arizona's 5th congressional district|the 5th District]]. His conception of term limits had evolved: in 2011 he stated that they were a flawed concept unless they were applied across the board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/Content/Protected/Articles/000/000/003/678yxbyn.asp |title=They Took the Pledge |publisher=Weeklystandard.com |date=2004-02-09 |accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref> His successor in Congress, [[Jeff Flake]], was giving up the seat to run for the [[United States Senate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/news/articles/2011/04/19/20110419matt-salmon-seeks-us-house-seat-brk.html|title=Matt Salmon seeks to replace Jeff Flake in U.S. House|date=April 19, 2011|accessdate=April 20, 2011|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|first=Jim|last=Walsh}}</ref> He was endorsed by the [[Club for Growth]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubforgrowth.org/endorsedcandidates/?subsec=0&id=991 |title=Matt Salmon (AZ-05) |publisher=Clubforgrowth.org |date= |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> Governor [[Jan Brewer]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Welch |first=Dennis |url=http://www.azfamily.com/news/politics/Gov-Brewer-makes-first-congressional-endorsement-backs-Salmon-161938475.html |title=Gov. Brewer makes first congressional endorsement, backs Salmon &#124; azfamily.com Phoenix |publisher=Azfamily.com |date=July 10, 2012 |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> Senator [[John Thune]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Catanese |first=David |url=http://www.politico.com//blogs/davidcatanese/0811/Thune_endorses_Matt_Salmon_.html |title=Thune endorses Matt Salmon \u2013 David Catanese |publisher=Politico.Com |date=August 2, 2011 |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> Congressman [[David Schweikert]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/david-catanese/2012/02/schweikert-endorses-salmon-113132.html |title=Schweikert endorses Salmon |publisher=Politico.Com |date= |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> Congressman [[Trent Franks]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Catanese |first=David |url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/davidcatanese/0411/Kyl_for_Adams_Franks_for_Salmon_.html |title=Kyl for Adams, Franks for Salmon \u2013 David Catanese |publisher=Politico.Com |date=April 28, 2011 |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> and former Florida Governor [[Jeb Bush]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salmonforcongress.com/article/breaking-governor-jeb-bush-endorses-matt-salmon |title=Breaking: Governor Jeb Bush Endorses Matt Salmon |publisher=Salmonforcongress.com |date= |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Nowicki |first=Dan |url=http://www.azcentral.com/arizonarepublic/local/articles/2012/08/17/20120817gingrich-adams-salmon-nowicki.html |title=Gingrich endorses Adams over his old House rival Salmon |publisher=Azcentral.com |date=August 18, 2012 |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref>  In the August 28 Republican primary, he defeated former state house speaker [[Kirk Adams]] 52%\u201348%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=724820 |title=AZ District 05 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Aug 28, 2012 |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Primary Election|url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/AZ/41012/98670/Web01/en/summary.html|accessdate=January 15, 2013|date=September 18, 2012}}</ref> In the general election, Salmon defeated Democrat Spencer Morgan 65%\u201335%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=706818 |title=AZ \u2013 District 05 Race \u2013 Nov 06, 2012 |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref>  However, the 5th is as heavily Republican as its predecessor, and Salmon had effectively assured his return to Congress with his primary victory.\n\nSalmon was reelected almost as easily in 2014.  However, he announced on February 25, 2016 that he is retiring for good.<ref name=PoliticoRetirement/>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn March 2013, he endorsed the idea of bringing back the [[Hastert Rule]], which is that in order to bring a bill to the floor it must have a majority of the majority party's support.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/blog/inside-politics/2013/mar/12/arizona-rep-matt-salmon-bring-back-hastert-rule/ |title=Arizona Rep. Matt Salmon: Bring back 'Hastert rule' |publisher=Washingtontimes.com |date=2013-03-12 |accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref>  He also proposed an amendment to the United States Constitution limiting House members to three terms in office and Senators to two.<ref>{{cite web|author=Matt Salmon |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hjres41?utm_campaign=govtrack_email_update&utm_source=govtrack/email_update&utm_medium=email |title=Proposing an amendment to the Constitution of the United States relative to limiting the number of terms that a Member of Congress may serve. (2013; 113th Congress H.J.Res. 41) |publisher=GovTrack.us |date=2013-04-23 |accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref>\n\n;Abortion\nSalmon is pro-life and has opposed federal funding of abortions as well as family-planning assistance that includes abortions.<ref name=issues>{{cite web| title =Matt Salmon (Republican, district 5) | work =On the Issues| url =http://www.ontheissues.org/house/Matt_Salmon.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title =Representative Matthew 'Matt' Salmon's Voting Records: Abortion| work =Project Vote Smart| url =http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/22184/matthew-salmon/2/abortion#.UbuXivk3upo}}</ref>\n\n;Gay rights\nSalmon voted to ban gay couples adopting children and opposes gay marriage.<ref name=issues/>\n\nIn April 2013, Salmon announced that he would continue to oppose [[same-sex marriage]] even though his son is openly gay.<ref name= views>{{cite news |title=Rep. Matt Salmon: Gay son hasn't changed my views on gay marriage |work= The Washington Post |first= Rachel |last= Weiner |date= April 1, 2013 |url= http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/04/01/rep-matt-salmon-gay-son-hasnt-changed-my-views-on-gay-marriage }}</ref> Salmon's stances have been unmoved despite his acceptance of his son's homosexuality.<ref>{{cite news|title=Matt Salmon's gay son talks Congressman father's same-sex marriage opposition, reparative therapy|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/04/09/matt-salmon-gay-son_n_3044858.html|work=HuffPost \u2013 Gay Voices|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=April 13, 2013|date=April 9, 2013|first=Curtis M.|last=Wong}}</ref> Salmon's son led the Arizona [[Log Cabin Republicans]]; he left the group to focus on medical school.<ref name= views/>\n\n;Civil Rights\nSalmon is strictly opposed to the surveillance of personal emails and phone-calls currently allowed and has called for legislation to reduce it.<ref name=salmon>{{cite web| title =Rep. Salmon Calls for Special Counsel to Investigate IRS Targeting of Conservative Groups| work =Matt Salmon: 5th District of Arizona| date =May 15, 2013| url =http://salmon.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-salmon-calls-for-special-counsel-to-investigate-irs-targeting-of}}</ref>  He introduced a bill that would better protect privacy rights by limiting the ability of the government to perform\nunwarranted searches.<ref>{{cite web| title =Salmon Introduces Bill to Protect Emails, Ensure Privacy from Government Entities| work =Matt Salmon: 5th District of Arizona| date =May 7, 2013| url =http://salmon.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/salmon-introduces-bill-to-protect-emails-ensure-privacy-from-government}}</ref>\n\n;Environment\nSalmon has been a moderate supporter of environmental protection.  He voted to enforce environmental standards on new pipelines, prohibit the EPA from being barred from investigations, reduce nuclear waste, and provide larger forest conservation.<ref name=issues/><ref>{{cite web| title =Representative Matthew 'Matt' Salmon's Voting Records Environment| work =Project Vote Smart| url =http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/22184/matthew-salmon/30/environmental-issues#.UbuuTPk3upo}}</ref>\n\n;Budget\nSalmon is a strong fiscal conservative and has often caused rifts and defections in his own party to oppose increasing the deficit.<ref name=hill>{{cite web| last =Trujillo| first =Mario| title =Rep. Matt Salmon swims against currents of the Republican establishment| work =The Hill| date =Mar 18, 2013| url =http://thehill.com/capital-living/new-member-of-the-week/288635-rep-matt-salmon-swims-against-currents-of-the-republican-establishment}}</ref>  He has strictly opposed raising the debt limit and any new spending without matching cuts.<ref name=debt>{{cite web| title =Rep. Salmon\u2019s Vote on Raising the Debt Ceiling| work =Matt Salmon: 5th District of Arizona| date =Jan 23, 2013| url =http://salmon.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-salmon-s-vote-on-raising-the-debt-ceiling}}</ref>  He believes government agencies and institutions should undergo reform, not expansion, to meet their needs.<ref>{{cite web| title =REP. SALMON: \"Medicaid needs reform, not expansion\"| work =Matt Salmon: 5th District of Arizona| date =Jan 23, 2013| url =http://salmon.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-salmon-medicaid-needs-reform-not-expansion}}</ref>\n\n;Taxes\nMatt Salmon signed the Taxpayer Protection Pledge, stating he would never vote for legislation to increase taxes on Americans.<ref>{{cite web| title =Matt Salmon Signs Taxpayer Protection Pledge| work =Salmon For Congress| date =Jun 8, 2011| url =http://www.salmonforcongress.com/article/matt-salmon-signs-taxpayer-protection-pledge\n}}</ref>  He opposes new government spending unless it has a plan to initiate some spending cut that will offset the loss.<ref name=debt/>  He has voted to cut various taxes, such as the estate and marriage taxes.<ref>{{cite web| title =Representative Matthew 'Matt' Salmon's Voting Records: Budget, Spending and Taxes| work =Project Vote Smart| url =http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/22184/matthew-salmon/10/budget-spending-and-taxes#.UbuvTfk3upo}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the recent IRS scandal and the wake of investigation, Salmon has called upon Attorney General Eric Holder to hold independent investigation on the IRS for its alleged targeting of its political opponents due allow for an unbiased non-government council to look into the matter.<ref name=salmon/>\n\nHe is a cosponsor to a bill that would prevent politically-based bias causing any discrimination in tax treatment.<ref name=salmon/>\n\nIn 2011 Salmon signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any Global Warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americansforprosperity.org/files/Salmon_Matt.pdf |format=PDF |title=Americans for Prosperity Applauds U.S. House Candidate Matt Salmon |publisher=Americansforprosperity.org |accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training|Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training]]\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions|Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Asia and the Pacific|Subcommittee on Asia and the Pacific]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere|Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere]] (Chair)\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Arizona Senate 21st District Election, 1990\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Matt Salmon'''\n|24,191\n|59.82\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Bill Hegarty\n|16,227\n|40.12\n|-\n|Write-in\n|Tom Wilkinson\n|24\n|0.06\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Arizona Senate 21st District Election, 1992\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Matt Salmon (inc.)'''\n|34,417\n|100.00\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Arizona 1st Congressional District Republican Primary Election, 1994\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\